        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Dirth Darkseeder</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>I want to share with you a few of the tentative conclusions I've reached regarding Mr. Volte's utterances. And I stress the word "tentative," because the subject of what motivates Volte is tricky and complex. You see, I unquestionably believe that Volte's ignorant attempts to debunk myths often lead to the perpetuation of them. And because of that belief, I'm going to throw politeness and inoffensiveness to the winds. In this letter, I'm going to be as rude and crude as I know how, to reinforce the point that one can consecrate one's life to the service of a noble idea or a glorious ideology. Volte, however, is more likely to create problems that our grandchildren will have to live with. Let his naive memoirs stand as evidence that if natural selection indeed works by removing the weakest and most genetically unfit members of a species, then he is clearly going to be the first to go. When Volte says that his musings are Right with a capital R, that's just a load of spucatum tauri. </P><P>Does he really know anything about the offhand remarks he claims to support? No, he doesn't. One of his former assistants, shortly after having escaped from Volte's iron veil of monolithic thought, stated, "No clear-thinking individual would have the temerity to nourish rude ideologies." This comment is typical of those who have finally realized that if there's an untold story here, it's that Volte is known for fabricating evidence. Let's remember that. Regardless of the theoretical beauty of the notion that the confusion that he creates is desirable and convenient to our national enemies, there is the opposing fact that I wonder what would happen if he really did glorify stolid, crotchety delinquents. There's a spooky thought. </P><P>What we have been imparting to Volte -- or what he has been eliciting from us -- is a half-submerged, barely intended logic, contaminated by wishes and tendencies we prefer not to acknowledge. I have a hard time trying to reason with people who remain calm when they see Volte open the gates of hell. He has found a way to avoid compliance with government regulations, circumvent any further litigation, and lead us, lemminglike, over the precipice of self-destruction -- all by trumping up a phony emergency. Volte's solutions are not pedantic treatises expressing theories or extravaganzas dealing in fables or fancies. They are substantial, sober outpourings from the very soul of exhibitionism. What I want to document now is that if you think that Volte's ultimata are not worth getting outraged about, then you're suffering from very serious nearsightedness. You're focusing too much on what he wants you to see and failing to observe many other things of much greater importance. </P><P>Should you think I'm saying too much, please note that Volte thinks that the boogeyman is going to get us if we don't agree to his demands. Of course, thinking so doesn't make it so. This raises the question: To what depths of depravity does he need to descend before the rest of us realize we must convince the government to clamp down hard on his writings? I've never gotten a clear and honest answer to that question from Volte. But what is clear is that once people obtain the critical skills that enable them to think and reflect and speculate independently, they'll realize that Volte's eccentricity is surpassed only by his vanity. And his vanity is surpassed only by his empty theorizing. (Remember his theory that propagandism is a noble goal?) As a matter of fact, he likes to cite poll results that "prove" that the cure for evil is more evil. Really? Have you ever been contacted by one of his pollsters? Chances are good that you have never been contacted and never will be. Otherwise, the polls would show that if Volte had done his homework, he'd know that his prank phone calls are not witty satire, as Volte would have you believe. They're simply the disruptive, ugly ramblings of someone who has no idea or appreciation of what he's mocking. </P><P>Volte can go on saying that laws are meant to be broken, but the rest of us have serious problems to deal with that preclude our indulging in such disdainful dreams just now. He wants us to feel sorry for the callow pickpockets who violate all the rules of decorum. I claim we should instead feel sorry for their victims, all of whom know full well that most of you reading this letter have your hearts in the right place. Now follow your hearts with actions. This screams of the old belief that incoherent vendors of nepotism are merely sullen, surly lunkheads. But there's the rub; in legal terminology, Volte is guilty of suppressio veri or "concealment of truth". Let me rephrase that: Volte is careless with data, makes all sorts of causal interpretations of things without any real justification, has a way of combining disparate ideas that don't seem to hang together, seems to show a sort of pride in his own biases, gets into all sorts of mindless speculation, and then makes no effort to test out his speculations -- and that's just the short list! How many of Volte's comrades are content to sit around doing absolutely nothing to contribute to the world around them? I'd hazard to guess that the number is pretty high. Please remember that Volte operates on an international scale to promote racial superiority doctrines, ethnic persecution, imperialist expansion, and genocide. It's only fitting, therefore, that we, too, work on an international scale, but to guide the world into an age of peace, justice, and solidarity. His latest manifesto, like all the ones that preceded it, is a consummate anthology of disastrously bad writing teeming with misquotations and inaccuracies, an odyssey of anecdotes that are occasionally entertaining, but certainly not informative. Still, the issue of what to do about Mr. Volte's homophobic, vapid litanies is far from settled. The letter you just read should be seen as a starting point for dialogue on this controversial issue.</P><P>P.S. Anyone can use a complaint generator.</P><P> </font></td>
